observations.recommendation:
We have recommended that the Management:

Thru the Inventory Committee, conduct physical inventory of all items of PPE of the Municipality, whether acquired through purchase or donation, including those constructed by administration and found at station, within the period prescribed under the aforementioned COA Circular;

b. Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile the same with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs;

c. Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and 

d. Direct the Municipal Accountant and GSO Designate to prepare, maintain and update Property Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, for each item of the PPE pursuant to Section 114, Paragraph 4 of the MNGAs for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended that Management:

a.	Create the Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members to conduct physical inventory of all PPEs of the Municipality within the period prescribed under the aforementioned COA Circular;

b.	Thru the Inventory Committee created, update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile with accounting records;

c.	Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and 

d.	After the inventory taking, direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the updated ledger cards for each item of the PPE pursuant to the Section 269 of the GAM for LGUs.

We recommended that the Management:
Thru the Inventory Committee, conduct physical inventory of all items of PPE of the Municipality, whether acquired through purchase or donation, including those constructed by administration and found at station, within the period prescribed under the aforementioned COA Circular;
Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile the same with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs;
Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant and GSO Designate to prepare, maintain and update Property Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, for each item of the PPE pursuant to Section 114, Paragraph 4 of the MNGAs for LGUs, Volume I.
The Management explained that they have already identified some of the items that have caused the discrepancy between the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment and the accounting records. They agreed to correct and reconcile their records and reports.

We recommended to management the following: 


a.	Direct the MSWDO and the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents to determine the propriety and validity of the disbursement and to avoid suspension and/or disallowance in audit;

b.	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that DVs are supported by complete documents in compliance with Section 4(6) of PD 1445;

c.	Direct the GSO and MSWDO to account the 178 bags of rice to determine whether these were not yet distributed and should be taken as inventory or if distributed, provide for the proof of acknowledgement from recipients; and

d.	Instruct all concerned departments who are receiving goods to inform and coordinate with the GSO for the inspection, receipt, preparation and maintenance of inventory list and stock cards of such goods, before issuance to the concerned end users or recipients.

We recommended that management strictly comply with the provisions embodied in the COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015 and IPSAS 17 by ensuring the following:

a.	Inventory Committee conducts inventory of Local Roads under the LGUs jurisdiction at year-end;

b.	General Service Officer maintains and updates a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all road and its component;

c.	Municipal Engineer provides the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components of road projects; and

d.	Municipal Accountant ensures compliance with the transitory provisions of the Circular by updating the records of the Road Network account and keeps and maintains subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network. Moreover, the Municipal Accountant must compute the depreciation expense, prepare the lapsing schedule and draw necessary journal entry to take up depreciation expense for the current year, update the related accumulated depreciation and record adjustment in government equity account for unrecorded prior years’ depreciation expense to present fairly the financial statements in accordance with IPSAS 17.

We recommended that management strictly comply with the provisions embodied in the COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015 and IPSAS 17 by ensuring the following:
a.	Inventory Committee conducts inventory of Local Roads under the LGUs jurisdiction at year-end;
b.	General Services Officer maintains and updates a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keeps a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all local roads and their components;
c.	Municipal Engineer provides the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components of road projects; and
d.	Municipal Accountant ensures compliance with the transitory provisions of the Circular by updating the records of the Road Network account and keeps and maintains subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network.

We recommended management the following:
Revert back to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund the total of P3,319,114.80 pertaining to unrecorded deposits or transfers to DRRM bank account in CYs 2011 and 2012;
Ensure that the unexpended balance of QRF and the DRRMF-MOOE at the end of the year will be transferred to the Special Trust Fund Account and will be recorded under the Trust Liabilities – DRRMF account;
Ensure that Continuing Appropriations/Capital Outlay of DRRMF will continue to be recorded under the General Fund books until the projects funded therefor are completed and should never be transferred to STF;
Set-up and maintain subsidiary ledgers for the special trust fund for unutilized DRRMF by year of transfer, receipts of NDRRMF by transferring agency, DRRMF from other LGUs by LGU, and other sources by donor in order to readily determine the balances of transfers/receipts; and
Reconcile and correct the Notes to Financial Statements by reflecting the correct balances of special trust fund by year.

